principles: [
      { q: `Look at these plurals: <span class="pq-ar">مُشْرِكُونَ</span> (polytheists) ، <span class="pq-ar">مُؤْمِنُونَ</span> (believers) ، <span class="pq-ar">مُسْلِمَاتٌ</span> (Muslim women). What do you notice about how each one ends?`, a: `Human plurals are made in three ways: ـونَ, ـينَ, or ـاتٌ.<br>ـونَ and ـينَ are used for a group of men, or a mixed group of men and women — they mean the exact same thing, and only differ in grammar, which you'll learn later.<br>ـاتٌ is used only for a group of women.<br><span class="pa-ar">مُشْرِكٌ ← مُشْرِكُونَ (polytheists) &nbsp;&nbsp; مُؤْمِنٌ ← مُؤْمِنُونَ (believers) &nbsp;&nbsp; مُسْلِمَةٌ ← مُسْلِمَاتٌ (Muslim women)</span>` },
      { q: `Look at these words: <span class="pq-ar">قَرْيَةٌ</span> ، <span class="pq-ar">عِبَادَةٌ</span> ، <span class="pq-ar">سَيِّئَةٌ</span>. What do they have in common?`, a: `They are all feminine. Any word with taa marbuta (ة) is feminine.` },
      { q: `Look at these plurals: <span class="pq-ar">أَصْنَامٌ</span> ، <span class="pq-ar">أَيَّامٌ</span> ، <span class="pq-ar">أَسْمَاءٌ</span>. What do they have in common?`, a: `They are all non-human plurals — as mentioned in Lesson 1, these are irregular and must be memorised. They are also feminine, since all non-human plurals are treated as feminine.` },
      { q: `<span class="pq-ar">أَصْنَامٌ</span> (idols) doesn't end in ة. So why does the adjective describing it — <span class="pq-ar">كَثِيرَةٌ</span> — take the feminine ending? And why doesn't it say <span class="pq-ar">كَثِيرُونَ</span>, given it's plural?`, a: `A word is feminine if it ends in taa marbuta (ة). Every non-human plural is also treated as feminine — even ones with no ة at all. That's why the adjective takes the feminine ending كَثِيرَةٌ instead of the human-plural ending كَثِيرُونَ.<br><span class="pa-ar">قَرْيَةٌ، عِبَادَةٌ</span> (taa marbuta)<br><span class="pa-ar">أَصْنَامٌ، أَيَّامٌ، أَسْمَاءٌ</span> (feminine anyway, no ة)` },
      { q: `Look at these pairs from the story: <span class="pq-ar">رَجُلٌ</span> → <span class="pq-ar">الرَّجُلُ</span>, and <span class="pq-ar">مُشْرِكٌ كَبِيرٌ</span> → <span class="pq-ar">الْمُشْرِكُ الْكَبِيرُ</span>. When "ال" gets added to the noun, what happens to its adjective?`, a: `A word is definite when it begins with "ال" (this usually translates to "the" in English). Adjectives must match their noun — if the noun has "ال", the adjective must also have "ال". If the noun has no "ال", the adjective must have no "ال" either.<br><span class="pa-ar">مُشْرِكٌ كَبِيرٌ ← الْمُشْرِكُ الْكَبِيرُ &nbsp;&nbsp; أَصْنَامٌ كَثِيرَةٌ ← الْأَصْنَامُ الْكَثِيرَةُ</span>` },
      { q: `Compare these two: <span class="pq-ar">هَذَا الصَّنَمُ</span> and <span class="pq-ar">هَذَا صَنَمٌ</span>. They look almost the same, but one just names something and the other is a full sentence. What's the one difference between them, and why does it change everything?`, a: `<span class="pa-ar">هَذَا الصَّنَمُ</span> means "this idol" — just a phrase, not yet a complete sentence, because the noun has "ال" (definite). <span class="pa-ar">هَذَا صَنَمٌ</span> means "this is an idol" — a full sentence, because the noun has no "ال" (indefinite). Adding or removing "ال" is the only difference, but it changes a phrase into a sentence, or a sentence into a phrase.<br><span class="pa-ar">هَذِهِ الْقَرْيَةُ (this village) ← → هَذِهِ قَرْيَةٌ (this is a village)</span>` }
    ]
