    principles: [
      { q: `Look at these pairs: <span class="pq-ar">ضَرَبَ ← ضُرِبَ</span>, <span class="pq-ar">كَسَرَ ← كُسِرَ</span>, <span class="pq-ar">أَلْقَى ← أُلْقِيَ</span>. We mentioned that past tense verbs have many fathas, but these ones don't — they follow a different pattern instead. What is the pattern, and why might it exist?`, a: `A passive verb is one where the subject receives the action instead of doing it. Instead of "Ibrahim broke the idol", you say "the idol was broken" — you don't need to mention who did it. In the past tense, the vowels change to a damma then a kasra.<br><span class="pa-ar">ضَرَبَ (he hit) ← ضُرِبَ (he was hit)</span><span class="pa-ar">كَسَرَ (he broke) ← كُسِرَ (it was broken)</span><span class="pa-ar">أَلْقَى (he threw) ← أُلْقِيَ (he was thrown)</span>` }
