    principles: [
      { q: `Look at these pairs: <span class="pq-ar">نَاصِرٌ ← مَنْصُورٌ</span>, <span class="pq-ar">كَاسِرٌ ← مَكْسُورٌ</span>. In the story, Allah <span class="pq-ar">نَصَرَ</span> (supported) Ibrahim. One pattern describes the one doing the supporting, the other describes the one being supported. Which is which?`, a: `The pattern "faa-il" (like <span class="pq-ar">نَاصِرٌ</span>) describes the doer — the one doing the action. The pattern "maf-ool" (like <span class="pq-ar">مَنْصُورٌ</span>) describes the done-to — the one receiving the action. Both come from the same root, so recognising the pattern tells you which role the word plays, even without knowing its meaning.<br><span class="pa-ar">نَاصِرٌ (supporter) → مَنْصُورٌ (the one supported)</span><span class="pa-ar">كَاسِرٌ (breaker) → مَكْسُورٌ (the one broken)</span>` }
